# RWisecondorX Code Review — Pass 2

**Scope (pass 2)**: All R source under `R/` (WisecondorX layer + full NIPTeR
layer) and `inst/scripts/`.
**Prior pass**: Original review items 1–28 (WisecondorX layer only) and
S-1–S-9 (scripts). Fixed items are listed at the end of this file.

---

## Section 1 — Upstream Python CLI wrappers (`wisecondorx_cli.R`)

### 1-A · Shadow-patch mechanism still active and still needed

**Status**: Required for CBS conformance — keep, but document.

`.with_wisecondorx_predict_patch()` copies the upstream Python package to a
tempdir and injects the bundled `inst/extdata/wisecondorx_CBS.R` before every
upstream `wisecondorx predict` call. This mechanism is correct and still
needed.

Action: Add a single-line block comment above `.bundled_wisecondorx_cbs_script()`
explaining why the shadow copy exists (conformance with the native CBS, not a
monkey-patch for bug fixes). This prevents future maintainers from removing it.

### 1-B · `.condathis_isolate()` mutates four process env vars and cwd

The function modifies `HOME`, `XDG_CACHE_HOME`, `XDG_DATA_HOME`,
`XDG_CONFIG_HOME`, and `cwd` for every upstream CLI call. Cleanup is now
correct (`on.exit` is registered before the mutations — the order matters and
is correct). However, this still makes any upstream condathis call non-reentrant
(a second call during the first's execution would double-restore). There is
currently no reentrance guard.

If this ever becomes a concern, a reference-count flag (`on.exit` increment/
decrement) would protect against it.

---

## Section 2 — Reference building (`rwisecondorx_newref.R`)

### 2-A · 26-parameter public signature

`rwisecondorx_newref()` now has 26 parameters — correctly documented, but
cognitively heavy for callers. The PCA-distance parameters (7 values) could
be grouped into a single `pca_distance` named list argument similar to how
`algorithm_params` is stored in the returned reference. This would cut the
visible signature to ~20 parameters and make override patterns cleaner.

Low priority — do not change if it breaks existing call sites.

### 2-B · `message()` calls inside `.build_sub_reference()`

`.build_sub_reference()` emits `message()` calls ("Building autosomal
reference...", "  Finding reference bins...", etc.). This makes the function
impure and hard to test silently. Extract progress reporting to the caller
(`rwisecondorx_newref()`) and pass a `verbose` flag or use a callback.

---

## Section 3 — Gender model (`rwisecondorx_utils.R`, `mclust_utils.R`)

### 3-A · `.mclust_fit_in_namespace()` requires at least one of `modelNames`/`equalPro`

`mclust_utils.R:20`: if both are NULL the function stops with an error.
This constraint is correct but the error message is not surfaced by the
public callers' documentation. Both `.mclust_gender_fit()` and `.mclust_fit()`
supply at least one — so no bug — but the precondition should be captured in
the function signature (e.g., assert-style stopifnot at top with a clear
message rather than a silent path-dependent stop).

---

## Section 4 — Prediction (`rwisecondorx_predict.R`)

### 4-A · `stringsAsFactors = FALSE` everywhere — still widespread

R ≥ 4.0 changed `stringsAsFactors` default to `FALSE`. The explicit argument
is now redundant. It appears in:

- `nipter_bin.R` (×3), `nipter_chi.R`, `nipter_gc.R`, `nipter_sex.R` (×2),
  `nipter_reference.R`, `nipter_control_qc.R` (×9), `nipter_gaunosome_score.R`,
  `nipter_gaunosome_report.R`, `nipter_sex_score.R`, `sample_metrics.R` (×3),
  `convert.R`, `aaa.R`.

Also in `read.csv`/`read.delim` calls in `sample_metrics.R`.

These are harmless but add noise. Remove in a single mechanical pass. The
minimum required R version should be pinned in `DESCRIPTION` as `R (>= 4.0)`
if not already.

---

## Section 5 — NIPTeR class system (`nipter_classes.R`)

### 5-A · `1:22` / `as.character(1:22)` widespread in new NIPTeR code

`1:22` evaluates to an integer sequence starting from 1, so `1:0` gives
`c(1, 0)` — a classic R footgun. The correct form is `seq_len(22L)`.

Occurrences found in new files:
- `nipter_classes.R`: lines 380, 662, 852, 894, 895, 1074
- `nipter_chi.R`: line 242
- `nipter_bin.R`: lines 352, 395, 498, 504, 523, 581
- `nipter_gc.R`: lines 48, 246, 281, 326, 444
- `bed_reader.R`: lines 64, 344, 374, 398, 513
- `nipter_control_qc.R`: lines 419, 469, 903
- `nipter_reference.R`: line 336
- `convert.R`: lines 328, 341

Fix mechanically with a single `sed` pass across the new files.

### 5-B · `NIPTControlGroup` `.cache` serializes stale values

The `.cache = new.env(parent = emptyenv())` property is a per-instance mutable
cache environment. The cache invalidation path is correct for in-process
mutation (`$samples<-` reinitializes `.cache`). However, `saveRDS`/`readRDS`
serializes the cache contents alongside the object — a deserialized reference
model may carry cached `fractions_auto` values that predate any post-load
sample changes.

Fix: replace `default = quote(new.env(parent = emptyenv()))` with `default =
quote(NULL)` and initialize lazily in the generic methods:

```r
S7::method(fractions_auto, CombinedControlGroup) <- function(cg) {
  if (is.null(cg@.cache)) cg@.cache <- new.env(parent = emptyenv())
  if (exists("fractions_auto", envir = cg@.cache, inherits = FALSE)) ...
}
```

Alternatively document the invariant: "Do not modify samples after
`saveRDS`/`readRDS`; re-build the cache by calling `fractions_auto()` once."

### 5-C · `.legacy_field` / `.legacy_set_field` shim layer growing

`nipter_classes.R` exports `~20` `.legacy_*` helpers and S7 `switch` dispatch
tables for backward-compat `$` and `[[` access on old S3 `NIPTeRSample`
objects. This layer will continue to grow with each new field. Set a concrete
deadline for dropping S3 support and add a `lifecycle::deprecate_soft()`
warning to the S3 paths.

---

## Section 6 — NIPTeR reference building (`nipter_reference.R`)

### 6-A · `outlier_threshold = 3` not exposed through `nipter_build_reference()`

`nipter_build_reference()` calls `.augment_reference_frame_for_sex()` which
internally calls `.annotate_reference_frame_sex(outlier_threshold = 3)`.
The `3` is not forwarded from the public API. A user who needs tighter or
looser sex-outlier classification (e.g., for a small cohort) has no way to
adjust this without modifying source.

Add `sex_outlier_threshold = 3L` to `nipter_build_reference()` and forward it.

### 6-B · `.nipt_reference_count_cols[1:22]` fragile numeric index

`nipter_reference.R:336`:
```r
frame[, .nipt_reference_count_cols[1:22], drop = FALSE]
```
This relies on the autosomal columns being the first 22 entries of
`.nipt_reference_count_cols`. This happens to be true (the vector is defined
as `paste0("NChrReads_", c(1:22, "X", "Y"))`), but a future reordering would
silently produce wrong results. Replace with:
```r
frame[, .nipt_reference_count_cols[seq_len(22L)], drop = FALSE]
```

---

## Section 7 — NIPTeR sex model (`nipter_sex.R`)

### 7-A · `nipter_y_unique_ratio()` writes two tempfiles per call

The function creates two BED tempfiles (`y_bed_path`, `nuclear_bed_path`),
writes them via `write.table()`, passes them to duckhts coverage, then
`unlink()`s them via `on.exit`. This is correct but creates a disk-write/
read round-trip for data that is already in R memory.

The duckhts API (`rduckhts_bam_bed_coverage`) requires a `bed_path` argument.
If a future Rduckhts version supports in-memory BED frames, remove the
tempfile path. For now: document the tempfile lifecycle with a comment.

### 7-B · `nipter_as_control_group()` silently removes duplicate sample names

`nipter_control.R:62`:
```r
if (any(dups)) {
  message("Removing ", sum(dups), " duplicate sample(s) by name.")
```
A `message()` is emitted but duplicate sample names are almost certainly a
bug in the caller's data. Promote to `warning()` or add a `stop_on_duplicate`
parameter (default `TRUE`).

---

## Section 8 — NIPTeR control-group QC (`nipter_control_qc.R`)

### 8-A · Bare `for (chrom in 1:22)` at line 469

```r
for (chrom in 1:22) {
  reg <- tryCatch(...)
}
```
Same `1:N` hazard as 5-A. Replace with `for (chrom in seq_len(22L))`.

---

## Section 9 — BED reader (`bed_reader.R`)

### 9-A · Double matrix construction when corrected columns are present

In both `.rows_to_nipter_combined()` and `.rows_to_nipter_sep()`, four raw
count matrices are always built. Then, when corrected values are available,
a second set of corrected matrices is also built. When both `use_corr_auto`
and `use_corr_sex` are `TRUE`, the raw matrices are never used. This wastes
O(n_bins × 4) memory allocations per call.

Fix: check `has_corrected` early and skip raw matrix construction when all
compartments will use corrected columns.

